ull,"caption":"","asset":{"entryTitle":"Big computingtech_1920x1080small","entryDescription":null,"sys":{"id":"b8145fa7-f1d1-4087-8f37-c1163ee5d42c","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"image","dataFormat":"asset","uri":"\u002Fresearch-image-library\u002Farticle-horizontal-hero-images\u002Fbig-computingtech-1920x1080small.xb8df684d.jpg"}}}},"entryTitle":"An equitable society depends on holding Big Computing firms to account"},"linkURL":null,"articleDate":null,"linkText":null,"articleReadingTime":null},{"entry":{"entryThumbnail":null,"image":{"altText":"AI, head and brain","transformations":null,"caption":"","asset":{"entryTitle":"23_0591 RFTW-Alekandar_Matic-AI-predict-mental-health- 1920x1080_heroRevise","entryDescription":null,"sys":{"id":"606dba3b-e579-4fd2-a0d0-477a476721bc","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"image","dataFormat":"asset","uri":"\u002Fresearch-image-library\u002Farticle-horizontal-hero-images\u002F23-0591-rftw-alekandar-matic-ai-predict-mental-health-1920x1080-herorevise.x7aad2042.jpg"}}},"featured":false,"articlePDF":{"entryTitle":"Can we use AI to predict mental health crises","entryDescription":null,"sys":{"id":"d794050b-eb0b-47df-94ac-96e7a9f5a16e","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"pdf","dataFormat":"asset","uri":"\u002Fresearch-assets\u002Farticle-PDFs\u002Fcan-we-use-ai-to-predict-mental-health-crises.pdf"}},"entryDescription":null,"standfirst":"The rising demand for mental healthcare is prompting hospitals to work on and identify novel methods of anticipating demand and better deploying their limited resources. Research led by Aleksandar Matic explores how machine learning could help.","sys":{"owner":"WINTERST","metadata":{},"workflow":{"id":"contensisEntryBasic","state":"versionComplete"},"dataFormat":"entry","isPublished":true,"availableLanguages":["en-GB"],"contentTypeId":"article","language":"en-GB","allUris":["\u002Fresearch\u002Fresearch-for-the-world\u002Fhealth\u002Fai-predict-mental-health-crises"],"uri":"\u002Fresearch\u002Fresearch-for-the-world\u002Fhealth\u002Fai-predict-mental-health-crises","version":{"publishedBy":"WINTERST","archived":null,"deleted":null,"createdBy":"WINTERST","created":"2023-11-07T14:03:41.8082158Z","versionNo":"2.0","modified":"2023-11-21T10:49:43.094582Z","modifiedBy":"WINTERST","published":"2023-11-21T10:49:46.3446077Z","archivedBy":null,"deletedBy":null},"versionStatus":"published","id":"52fe060c-5490-480b-832a-81102ea9519b","projectId":"researchForTheWorld","slug":"can-we-use-ai-to-predict-mental-health-crises","properties":{}},"title":"Can we use AI to predict mental health crises?","body":[{"type":"content","value":"\u003Cp\u003ENearly one billion people worldwide are living with a mental health disorder. With demand for mental health care rising, there is a strong need to pro-actively anticipate patient demand, improve patient outcomes and decrease long-term costs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Farticles\u002Fs41591-022-01811-5\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003EResearch\u003C\u002Fa\u003E led by Visiting Fellow Dr Aleksandar Matic from the Department of Psychological and Behavioural Science at LSE and R&amp;D Director at Koa Health, aims to tackle these concerns by using machine learning to help predict mental health crises in patients so they can be prevented and caseloads can be better managed.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EConducted using the records of patients who had suffered at least one previous mental health crisis event, the research works on the assumption that historical patterns can predict future crises. A crisis is described as a situation where a patient can neither care for themselves nor function effectively in the community, and where they may hurt themselves or others.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"quote","value":{"text":"The model works by finding patterns in patient journeys which suggest an upcoming crisis and are too complex for humans to infer. "}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Ch2\u003EFinding patterns in patient journeys\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETo carry out the study, the researchers explored how to develop machine learning algorithms by leveraging the anonymous health record data of over 17,000 patients spanning seven years to accurately predict the risk of a crisis in a 28-day period.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The model works by finding patterns in patient journeys which suggest an upcoming crisis and are too complex for humans to infer,&rdquo; explains Dr Matic, who also works as R&amp;D Director at \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.koahealth.com\u002F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003EKoa Health\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a digital mental healthcare provider. &ldquo;Much like predictive text on your phone which detects a pattern and gives you a recommendation for the word you are trying to type, machine learning in this case examines patterns in patient journeys to predict what could come next.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThree different variables of data were fed into the algorithm. Firstly, the researchers inputted static data about patients such as their age, gender and diagnosis. Secondly, they included information from the patient&rsquo;s latest assessment and interaction with the hospital, including the severity and number of previous crisis events. Finally, they inputted variables representing time elapsed since registered events such as the patient&rsquo;s last crisis, their last contact with the hospital and since their last referral. Using this information, the algorithm was able to continuously monitor patients for risk of a mental health crisis over a period of 28 days.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe researchers found that, in 64 per cent of cases, the machine learning predictions were deemed &ldquo;clinically valuable&rdquo; in terms of either managing caseloads or mitigating risk. More specifically, clinicians reported the predictions were useful for preventing crises in 19 per cent of cases, identifying the deterioration of a patient&rsquo;s condition in 17 per cent of cases and managing caseload priorities in 28 per cent of cases.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is further work to do to improve accuracy, these results show that machine learning can play a major role in predicting preventing and mitigating mental health crises.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EThe problem with electronic records\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHowever, one of the main limitations in this area currently stems from the quality of electronic records and structure of our healthcare system. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m surprised we achieved the accuracy we did in this study due to the problems with electronic health records as a data source &ndash; they can be sparse, there are biases and there are errors,&rdquo; explains Dr Matic.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The reactive episodic nature of how mental healthcare is often delivered means patients come to hospital when they&rsquo;re already sick so there are gaps in the data. We don&rsquo;t know what&rsquo;s happened between their hospital visits. We show in the paper that the accuracy of predictions changes significantly depending on the gaps in the data. If you don&rsquo;t have any information on patients for two years, you can&rsquo;t really predict anything.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe researchers found lack of records for more than three months resulted in a seven per cent drop in accuracy and missing records for more than six months to a year contributed to a 13 per cent to 20 per cent drop\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"quote","value":{"text":"I don’t think technology will, or should, replace psychologists or psychiatrists but it could help scale their support better."}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Ch2\u003EWe need to shift from episodic to proactive healthcare\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDr Matic believes part of the solution is building technology that can shift the paradigm from mental healthcare delivered episodically or reactively to a more continuous proactive healthcare that is digitally supported.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor example, he argues we can start by making patients aware of mental health risk factors and empowering them to address some of these risks. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not talking about the most serious cases here,&rdquo; he clarifies. &ldquo;The area where the most unmet need lies is where people have mild or moderate symptoms. In these cases, technology and digital therapies could help. I don&rsquo;t think technology will, or should, replace psychologists or psychiatrists but it could help scale their support better, reduce the face time needed with therapists and close the gap for people with mild or moderate symptoms who are likely to benefit from self-serve tools.\"\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHe suggests healthcare data collected via smartphones, for instance, could also help support a continuous care model with these devices providing psychological data and information on day-to-day behaviours such as sleep, mobility patterns, and physical activity levels.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWith an \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nao.org.uk\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002F2023\u002F02\u002FProgress-in-improving-mental-health-services-CS.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003Eestimated 1.2 million people\u003C\u002Fa\u003E currently on waiting lists for NHS mental health services in England, anything that helps manage caseloads sounds promising but are there any concerns around using technology for this purpose?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDr Matic believes there are some challenges but transparency is key. &ldquo;Unknown biases are very important and every sample will be biased until we have a critical mass of data,&rdquo; he says. With this in mind, the same scientific team is working on replicating this research and testing the algorithm in various healthcare systems in different countries to ensure the results are consistent. A recent replication study in the US has produced consistent findings.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs we face an ever-growing mental health emergency, one thing is abundantly clear: anything that can help patients, mitigate risks and manage caseloads is certainly worth exploring.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDr Aleksandar Matic was speaking to Charlotte Kelloway, Media Relations Manager at LSE.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"callout","value":{"content":"\u003Cp\u003E\"\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Farticles\u002Fs41591-022-01811-5\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" data-auth=\"NotApplicable\" data-linkindex=\"0\"\u003EMachine learning model to predict mental health crises from electronic health records\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\" by&nbsp;Roger Garriga, Javier Mas, Semhar Abraha, Jon Nolan, Oliver Harrison, George Tadros,&nbsp; and Aleksandar Matic was published in \u003Cem\u003ENature Medicine \u003C\u002Fem\u003E(2022).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\"\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1038\u002Fs41591-022-01820-4\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003EMachine learning paves the way toward the prevention of mental health crises\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\" by Roger Garriga and Aleksandar Matic. was published in \u003Cem\u003ENature Medicine \u003C\u002Fem\u003E(2022).&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\"\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cell.com\u002Fcell-reports-medicine\u002Ffulltext\u002FS2666-3791(23)00437-8#%20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003ECombining clinical notes with structured electronic health records enhances the prediction of mental health crises\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\" by Roger Garriga, Teodora Sandra Buda, Jo&atilde;o Guerreiro, Jes&uacute;s Oma&ntilde;a Iglesias, I&ntilde;aki Estella Aguerri, and Aleksandar Matić was published in \u003Cem\u003ECell Reports Medicine.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"}},{"type":"subscribeCTA","value":{"button":{"link":{"entryTitle":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","entryDescription":null,"entryThumbnail":null,"sys":{"id":"c1172d9b-6099-482e-abe5-64edf41c84b8","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"link","dataFormat":"entry","uri":null}},"text":"Subscribe"},"link":{"entryTitle":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","entryDescription":null,"entryThumbnail":null,"sys":{"id":"c1172d9b-6099-482e-abe5-64edf41c84b8","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"link","dataFormat":"entry","uri":null}},"description":"\u003Cp\u003ESign up to receive our newsletter: a bi-monthly digest of the latest social science research articles, podcasts and videos from LSE.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","title":"Interested in research like this?"}}],"thumbnailImageVertical":{"altText":"","transformations":null,"caption":"","asset":{"entryTitle":"23_0591_RFTW_Alekandar_Matic-AI-predict-mental-health-1920x10805_thumbnail1920x1920","entryDescription":null,"sys":{"id":"7bda0f71-f1a6-43c1-9b72-4f213bab2155","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"image","dataFormat":"asset","uri":"\u002Fresearch-image-library\u002Farticle-vertical-images-thumb\u002F23-0591-rftw-alekandar-matic-ai-predict-mental-health-1920x10805-thumbnail1920x1920.x0260ce57.jpg"}}},"readingTime":"5 min read","thumbnailImageHorizontal":{"altText":"","transformations":null,"caption":"","asset":{"entryTitle":"23_0591_RFTW_Alekandar_Matic_AI-predict-mental-health-1920x10802_meta","entryDescription":null,"sys":{"id":"fef7ffe4-d01a-46d4-bb29-d3a5255ac2ff","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"image","dataFormat":"asset","uri":"\u002Fresearch-image-library\u002F23-0591-rftw-alekandar-matic-ai-predict-mental-health-1920x10802-meta.x7b575443.jpg"}}},"featuredAcademic":[{"entryTitle":"Aleksandar Matic","entryDescription":null,"entryThumbnail":null,"sys":{"id":"bc6ae059-b150-4a0e-bfb5-2ad0b21f5275","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"person","dataFormat":"entry","uri":null}}],