"5c52f2f7-857c-4cee-bb94-2f110e5a4a00","projectId":"researchForTheWorld","slug":"screen-time-why-we-cant-stop-checking-our-phones","properties":{}},"title":"Screen time: why we can’t stop checking our phones","body":[{"type":"content","value":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen was the last time you checked your phone and scrolled through your notifications?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EChances are, the last time you did this, you didn&rsquo;t even realise it. &ldquo;Lots of people have developed certain patterns and habits when using their phones. Some of these interactions are conscious but many are unconscious and automatic,&rdquo; explains Dr Maxi Heitmayer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENow a Teaching Fellow in the Department of Psychological and Behavioural Science at LSE, Dr Heitmayer started investigating how we interact with our smartphones as a PhD student who had grown up with the advent and boom of social media.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAgainst a maelstrom of media stories about the addictive nature of smartphones, Dr Heitmayer initially set out to study how people use their phones to gain insight into how technology firms could make them less disruptive.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHowever, he quickly discovered the issue was not with the hardware of smartphones but with the people using them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"quote","value":{"text":"I watched the videos back with the participants and saw their honest and frequent surprise at how often they were checking their phones. "}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Everyone believes their phone is distracting them but our research shows that, actually, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fpii\u002FS0747563220303848\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003Eusers are distracting themselves\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. If you put your phone on to silent and then check it proactively there&rsquo;s no way for any designer to combat that,&rdquo; he says.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EGetting a handle on our habits\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn fact, Dr Heitmayer&rsquo;s research shows that a staggering 89 per cent of smartphone interactions are initiated by the user, with only 11 per cent prompted by an alert from the phone.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFurther analysis shows that about \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdl.acm.org\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1145\u002F3447526.3472026\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003Ea quarter of smartphone interactions are while the phone is on locked screen\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; with users frequently picking up or glancing at their phones to check for notifications.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDr Heitmayer finds that people are more likely to check their phones when switching between activities. For example, in between sending out an email and moving onto the next task on their to-do list. They also check their phones more frequently during particularly stressful work &ldquo;&lsquo;to give their minds a break&rdquo;&rsquo; or during dull tasks such as commuting.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETo carry out this research, Dr Heitmayer analysed the smartphone use of 37 participants aged 21 to 29 years old. Participants were provided with small cameras fixed on glasses enabling them to film their everyday phone use. Over 200 hours of video was recorded and analysed.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I watched the videos back with the participants and saw their honest and frequent surprise at how often they were checking their phones. Often, they had no idea why they were picking them up. This led to a rerouting of my research. It&rsquo;s a fallacy to believe technology will solve this problem for us. Nobody is going to be able to design a phone in a &lsquo;better&rsquo; way if we continue to use them the way we do currently; we need to develop ourselves and our habits to use these things more productively,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"quote","value":{"text":"It’s a fallacy to believe technology will solve this problem for us. Nobody is going to be able to design a phone in a ‘better’ way if we continue to use them the way we do currently. "}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Ch2\u003EA mobile education\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESo how can we do this? Dr Heitmayer believes the answer is in digital literacy education from a young age. There&rsquo;s lots of information for younger people about not getting your personal data stolen or on how to protect against online grooming, but Dr Heitmayer also believes we need education on how to put our phones down and switch off from them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The analogy I often use is cars,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;Cars are really useful, but we don&rsquo;t just let anyone use them as they&rsquo;re incredibly dangerous, too. We make people get a driving licence and go through a training process which teaches them how to use cars in the right way. I&rsquo;m not saying we need a smartphone licence, but we do need training on how to use these things and how to \u003Cem\u003Eput them down\u003C\u002Fem\u003E &ndash; and this should be done at the earliest age possible.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EReturn of the brick phone?\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut are we already taking matters into our own hands? With increasing talk of &ldquo;digital detoxes&rdquo; - where people take a break from technology - and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mirror.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fuk-news\u002Fnokia-6310-brick-phone-back-24629499\"\u003Ethe comeback of more basic phones\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with internet (often nicknamed &ldquo;brick phones&rdquo; after their cumbersome design), does Dr Heitmayer believe we will see large-scale backlash against smartphones?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn short, no. Although he has seen an increasing trend amongst some of his students to use two phones - a simple phone without internet for emergencies while out and about - and a smartphone to use for pleasure while at home, he doesn&rsquo;t think smartphones will see a significant drop in use.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Smartphones are the single most powerful tool that we have invented. They serve all our purposes in our private lives and professional lives; we use them to pay for public transport, for our groceries, to organise a technician to fix the plumbing... smartphones are just too useful for us all to stop using them.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWith smartphones seemingly here to stay, the next step for Dr Heitmayer is to identify and define the environmental factors that trigger us to pick up our phones so we can better understand our habits and ultimately become the master of them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDr Maxi Heitmayer was speaking to Charlotte Kelloway, Media Relations Manager at LSE.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"subscribeCTA","value":{"button":{"link":{"entryTitle":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","entryDescription":null,"entryThumbnail":null,"sys":{"id":"c1172d9b-6099-482e-abe5-64edf41c84b8","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"link","dataFormat":"entry","uri":null}},"text":"Subscribe"},"link":{"entryTitle":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","entryDescription":null,"entryThumbnail":null,"sys":{"id":"c1172d9b-6099-482e-abe5-64edf41c84b8","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"link","dataFormat":"entry","uri":null}},"description":"\u003Cp\u003ESign up to receive our newsletter: a bi-monthly digest of the latest social science research articles, podcasts and videos from LSE\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","title":"Interested in research like this?"}}],"thumbnailImageVertical":null,"readingTime":"4 min read","thumbnailImageHorizontal":{"altText":"","transformations":null,"caption":"","asset":{"entryTitle":"Heitmayer_screentime_1920x1080","entryDescription":null,"sys":{"id":"af2be764-3a6f-4813-8475-3bfd73ee4b8