Id":"researchForTheWorld","slug":null,"properties":{"filename":"climate-legislation-and-litigation.pdf","fileSize":254309,"filePath":"\u002Fresearch-assets\u002Farticle-PDFs\u002F","fileId":"4129ff2a-3474-4365-949e-795e4a72492b"}},"title":"climate-legislation-and-litigation","entryTitle":"climate-legislation-and-litigation"},"entryDescription":null,"standfirst":"The last five years have seen a surge in climate action cases, with individuals and environmental NGOs taking governments and corporations to court. Joana Setzer has been tracking these cases worldwide, exploring new trends in climate litigation. ","sys":{"owner":"WINTERST","metadata":{},"workflow":{"id":"contensisEntryBasic","state":"versionComplete"},"dataFormat":"entry","isPublished":true,"availableLanguages":["en-GB"],"contentTypeId":"article","language":"en-GB","allUris":["\u002Fresearch\u002Fresearch-for-the-world\u002Fsustainability\u002Fclimate-legislation-and-litigation"],"uri":"\u002Fresearch\u002Fresearch-for-the-world\u002Fsustainability\u002Fclimate-legislation-and-litigation","version":{"publishedBy":"REEDH","archived":null,"deleted":null,"createdBy":"WINTERST","created":"2024-02-26T10:25:44.129419Z","versionNo":"3.0","modified":"2024-04-22T07:56:19.0127706Z","modifiedBy":"REEDH","published":"2024-04-22T07:56:24.9699554Z","archivedBy":null,"deletedBy":null},"versionStatus":"published","id":"991d2b0b-73a9-4837-baf1-6d8840a47a93","projectId":"researchForTheWorld","slug":"passing-climate-legislation-is-not-enough-explaining-the-rise-in-climate-action-cases","properties":{}},"title":"Why are climate action cases rising?","body":[{"type":"content","value":"\u003Cp\u003EIn 2015, a groundbreaking ruling issued by a district court in the Netherlands captured global attention. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.urgenda.nl\u002Fen\u002Fthemas\u002Fclimate-case\u002F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003EThe case\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, which called for more ambitious action on climate change, had been filed by environmental non-profit foundation Urgenda against the Dutch government.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe courts upheld their claim and ruled the government had an explicit duty to protect the human rights of the Dutch population against climate change and to reduce emissions. This ruling directly led to more stringent climate policy and a phase out of coal power stations in the country.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESince this landmark judgment, we have seen an explosion of climate action cases across the world. Individuals and non-profit organisations are taking governments and corporations to court for not meeting their climate obligations. And not only that, they&rsquo;re winning &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.lse.ac.uk\u002Fgranthaminstitute\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002F2023\u002F06\u002FGlobal_trends_in_climate_change_litigation_2023_snapshot.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003Emore than 50 per cent of these cases\u003C\u002Fa\u003E have seen outcomes favourable to stronger climate action.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDr Joana Setzer and colleagues at the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.lse.ac.uk\u002Fgranthaminstitute\u002F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"\u003EGrantham Research Institute on Climate Change and the Environment\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at LSE release \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.lse.ac.uk\u002Fgranthaminstitute\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002F2023\u002F06\u002FGlobal_trends_in_climate_change_litigation_2023_snapshot.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"\u003Ean annual report\u003C\u002Fa\u003E exploring the global trends in climate litigation. The Grantham Research Institute collaborates with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fclimate.law.columbia.edu\u002F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"\u003EThe Sabin Center for Climate Change Law\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at Columbia Law School to identify cases worldwide, and it maintains the most comprehensive global resource on climate policy and legislation &ndash; the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fclimate-laws.org\u002F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"\u003EClimate Change Laws of the World database\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"quote","value":{"text":"There is a growing sense of frustration that the law and passing legislation are not enough. "}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Ch2\u003EAn explosion in climate cases\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We have seen a big increase in climate cases in the last ten years or so and there are several interconnected reasons behind why this could be the case,&rdquo; explains Dr Setzer. &ldquo;Firstly, there has been an increase in awareness of the climate problem &ndash; the causes, the consequences and the urgency of acting. The science on this is very robust and we have a better understanding of the problems as a society. This helps provide the evidence needed for litigation.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EShe continues: &ldquo;Secondly, there is a growing sense of frustration that the law and passing legislation are not enough. Seeing heads of state go to international conferences and shake hands over new agreements is promising but not good enough. Often these promises don&rsquo;t translate into action.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ELitigation is helpful for setting legal precedents and establishing frameworks for similar issues in the future. It can also help enforce rights that might exist on paper but not in reality.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor example, we are currently awaiting judgment from the European Court of Human Rights on a group of three climate cases. One of these cases was \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-europe-66923590\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003Ebrought by six young people from Portugal against 33 European countries\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. They claim their right to life has been violated by the inaction of these states and their failure to reduce emissions to meet the Paris Agreement target of limiting global warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the young people are calling for more stringent cuts on emissions, but in other cases claimants ask for compensation for harms incurred or a mixture of both future commitments and remuneration. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"videoPlayer","value":{"transcript":null,"videoDescription":null,"credits":null,"lsePlayerVideoGUID":null,"type":"YouTube","youTubeEmbed":"\u003Ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fembed\u002F1AesJonJsDc?si=S3qbygSB5cZM1kOV\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" allowfullscreen\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E","videoTitle":"The last five years has seen an explosion of climate action cases. Dr Joana Setzer talks about what this means for climate litigation."}},{"type":"quote","value":{"text":"The government is being sued from both sides and these cases can cost billions. "}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Ch2\u003EGreenwashing and reputational damage&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHowever, litigation is not just something which can be used as a last resort, it can also be used as part of a wider campaign to raise awareness and start conversations round climate issues. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not just about the case itself but about creating momentum and bringing people together,&rdquo; says Dr Setzer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEven decisions unfavourable to climate action can create changes in behaviour. Corporations have their public image and share prices to consider. Dr Setzer and colleagues at the Grantham Research Institute already found that fossil fuel companies register a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.lse.ac.uk\u002Fgranthaminstitute\u002Fpublication\u002Fimpacts-of-climate-litigation-on-firm-value\u002F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003Edrop in value\u003C\u002Fa\u003E after litigation or unfavourable judgments in climate lawsuits. The fact that cases are being filed has already resulted in corporations taking this into consideration as a risk factor and changing their behaviour accordingly.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd it&rsquo;s not just governments and fossil fuel companies that have to be careful. Brands that we perceive as more friendly to the environment are also being taken to court for &ldquo;greenwashing&rdquo; and making climate claims they can&rsquo;t substantiate. Take the oat milk company Oatly, for example, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fbusiness-60128075\"\u003Ewhose adverts were banned in 2022\u003C\u002Fa\u003E by the Advertising Standards Authority over misleading environmental claims.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EBacklash cases\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHowever, what works one way also works another, and we are seeing a rise in &ldquo;backlash&rdquo; cases with corporations using litigation against climate regulations or NGOs. For example, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fbusiness\u002F2023\u002Fnov\u002F09\u002Fshell-sues-greenpeace-over-fossil-fuel-protest-in-north-sea\"\u003EShell recently filed a lawsuit against Greenpeace\u003C\u002Fa\u003E for $2.1million in damages after its campaigners boarded an oil platform last year.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWe have also seen a rise in anti-ESG (environmental, social and governance) cases in the US where companies are trying to stop legislation that promotes ESG policy or incorporates it into financial services. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a risk that makes the game uglier,&rdquo; warns Dr Setzer. &ldquo;You have litigation coming from all directions, and those with less power and resources are likely to struggle more to pay for legal fees and costs.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWe are seeing also an \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.lse.ac.uk\u002Fgranthaminstitute\u002Fnews\u002Finvestor-state-dispute-settlement-as-a-new-avenue-for-climate-change-litigation\u002F\"\u003Euptick in arbitration cases\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with fossil fuel companies taking governments to court for limiting their rights to operate. After the groundbreaking Urgenda case outlined above which called for the Dutch government to phase out coal, two coal companies then filed an arbitration case against the government for taking away their authority to operate.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The government is being sued from both sides and these cases can cost billions,&rdquo; explains Dr Setzer. The two companies in this example have \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.somo.nl\u002Fenergy-giant-rwe-withdraws-billion-euro-claim-against-the-netherlands\u002F\"\u003Enow withdrawn from arbitration\u003C\u002Fa\u003E but these cases are a perfect example of similar action that could be taken in the future.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWith climate becoming an ever more prominent issue and with frustrations growing at a lack of action by both states and corporations, climate cases look set to increase even further, especially with the rise of far-right governments around the world.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGoing forwards, Dr Setzer and colleagues will continue to track and report on climate litigation alongside undertaking new work to understand the impact of these interventions on changing policies and behaviours and how science can inform and support further litigation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDr Joana Setzer was speaking to Charlotte Kelloway, Media Relations Manager at LSE.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"callout","value":{"content":"\u003Cp\u003ERead more from Joana Setzer with Juliana V&eacute;lez Echeverri and Catherine Higham in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogs.lse.ac.uk\u002Fbusinessreview\u002F2024\u002F04\u002F17\u002Fclimate-washing-litigation-deters-misinformation-but-can-it-help-cut-emissions\u002F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003E&ldquo;Climate-washing&rdquo; litigation deters misinformation, but can it help cut emissions?\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&nbsp;on the LSE Business Review Blog, and register for the LSE public event \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.lse.ac.uk\u002FEvents\u002F2024\u002F06\u002F202406271830\u002Ftrend\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003EGlobal trends in climate litigation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E on 27 June 2024.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"}},{"type":"subscribeCTA","value":{"button":{"link":{"entryThumbnail":null,"entryDescription":null,"sys":{"owner":"WINTERST","metadata":{},"workflow":{"id":"contensisEntryBasic","state":"versionComplete"},"dataFormat":"entry","isPublished":true,"availableLanguages":["en-GB"],"contentTypeId":"link","language":"en-GB","allUris":[],"uri":null,"version":{"publishedBy":"REEDH","archived":null,"deleted":null,"createdBy":"WINTERST","created":"2023-09-04T13:33:47.5503724Z","versionNo":"1.0","modified":"2023-09-04T13:33:47.5503724Z","modifiedBy":"WINTERST","published":"2023-09-05T13:14:41.1236311Z","archivedBy":null,"deletedBy":null},"versionStatus":"published","id":"c1172d9b-6099-482e-abe5-64edf41c84b8","projectId":"researchForTheWorld","slug":"research-for-the-world-newsletter-sign-up","properties":{}},"title":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","entryTitle":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","url":"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.alumni.lse.ac.uk\u002Fs\u002F1623\u002Finterior-hybrid.aspx?sid=1623&gid=1&pgid=6055"},"text":"Subscribe"},"link":{"entryThumbnail":null,"entryDescription":null,"sys":{"owner":"WINTERST","metadata":{},"workflow":{"id":"contensisEntryBasic","state":"versionComplete"},"dataFormat":"entry","isPublished":true,"availableLanguages":["en-GB"],"contentTypeId":"link","language":"en-GB","allUris":[],"uri":null,"version":{"publishedBy":"REEDH","archived"