 health. Thomas Curran speaks about his research into the dark side of perfectionist culture.","sys":{"owner":"zengenti","metadata":{},"workflow":{"id":"contensisEntryBasic","state":"versionComplete"},"dataFormat":"entry","isPublished":true,"availableLanguages":["en-GB"],"contentTypeId":"article","language":"en-GB","allUris":["\u002Fresearch\u002Fresearch-for-the-world\u002Fhealth\u002Fover-stressed-and-under-pressure-the-problem-with-being-perfect"],"uri":"\u002Fresearch\u002Fresearch-for-the-world\u002Fhealth\u002Fover-stressed-and-under-pressure-the-problem-with-being-perfect","version":{"publishedBy":"REEDH","archived":null,"deleted":null,"createdBy":"zengenti","created":"2020-08-14T09:08:10.6501103Z","versionNo":"33.0","modified":"2023-11-13T11:45:19.2154878Z","modifiedBy":"REEDH","published":"2023-11-13T11:45:24.4855788Z","archivedBy":null,"deletedBy":null},"versionStatus":"published","id":"eddb1198-e8a2-414b-8b41-98d23948badd","projectId":"researchForTheWorld","slug":"over-stressed-and-under-pressure-the-problem-with-being-perfect","properties":{}},"title":"The problem with perfection","body":[{"type":"content","value":"\u003Cp\u003EFor many people, perfectionism is an asset. It is commonly used in the workplace to describe dedication, attention to detail, or extremely high standards for yourself and others - goals to aspire to if you want to be successful.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut Dr Thomas Curran wants us to challenge this view. Research he conducted with Andrew Hill into perfectionism culture in the UK and US since the mid-1990s has revealed that increasing numbers of people are experiencing \"multidimensional perfectionism\". This describes a phenomenon where three kinds of perfectionism are simultaneously endured, meaning we are surrounded by endless pressure to reach unobtainable levels of achievement measured against ever-widening criteria.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDr Curran cites three dimensions of perfectionism conceptualised by psychologists Paul Hewitt and Gordon Flett: socially prescribed perfectionism, other-oriented perfectionism, and self-oriented perfectionism. Each dimension has a different pressure point: socially prescribed perfectionists believe that others expect them to be perfect;&nbsp;other-oriented perfectionists place high-demands on other people; and self-oriented perfectionists expect flawlessness of themselves.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"videoPlayer","value":{"transcript":null,"videoDescription":null,"credits":null,"lsePlayerVideoGUID":"2eb87783-4d40-4d81-ac21-6026772d6e3d","type":"YouTube","youTubeEmbed":"\u003Ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fembed\u002F_KnH1WPH2u4\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E","videoTitle":"Watch: Is perfectionism an illness? This short film features research by Thomas Curran."}},{"type":"quote","value":{"text":"Images of others at carefully selected moments of their lives has distorted our perceptions of their lifestyles and careers."}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Ch2\u003EAiming for perfection can have a personal toll\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EMaking the best of oneself sounds like an admirable goal. However Dr Curran&rsquo;s research has found that when people fail &ndash;&nbsp;especially in the presence of others &ndash;&nbsp;they feel a profound sense of guilt and shame for what they perceive to be a defective performance from a flawed self. Furthermore, his findings connect the rise of perfectionism to the growing number of cases of mental illnesses &ndash; such as eating disorders, anxiety and depression &ndash; particularly among young people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEach form of perfectionism comes with \"negative baggage\" Dr Curran says, but this is particularly acute with those that suffer from socially prescribed perfectionism. &ldquo;Socially prescribed perfectionists don&rsquo;t feel valued in social situations and have a chronic need for other people&rsquo;s approval, while being extremely down on their implicit value,\" he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhile some may view perfectionism as a \"necessary evil\" that helps people become become highly successful, Dr Curran argues that this is a myth, and that in fact perfectionism can be detrimental to performance and health. &ldquo;There is a lot of evidence to say you are not going to get any real performance benefit from perfectionism, and that it&rsquo;s actually really damaging for lots of people,\" he adds.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"audioPlayer","value":{"transcript":null,"ctaButtonLink":null,"audioDescription":null,"markup":null,"credits":null,"lseAudioGUID":"49b78d7a-8895-46d5-b1a4-f2d3fe561c99","audio":null,"audioTitle":"Listen: Is perfect the enemy of the possible? Hear Thomas Curran in this episode of the LSE iQ podcast.","ctaButtonText":null,"poster":null}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Cp\u003EIn his upcoming book,&nbsp;\u003Cem\u003EImperfect,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003EDr Curran focuses on the culture of perfectionism and the wider environmental factors that have led to its rise. One of the book's major themes is an exploration of why levels of socially-prescribed perfectionism have shown a marked increase since the mid-1990s.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I found that our world has become increasingly globalised over the last 25 years, with the opening up of borders to trade and employment, and much higher levels of travel,&rdquo; he explains. &ldquo;In the past we were judged more on a local scale, but with the opening of economies what we are seeing is that people are being exposed to these additional global ideals of perfection.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"videoPlayer","value":{"transcript":null,"videoDescription":null,"credits":null,"lsePlayerVideoGUID":"49b78d7a-8895-46d5-b1a4-f2d3fe561c99","type":"YouTube","youTubeEmbed":"\u003Ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fembed\u002F_KnH1WPH2u4\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E","videoTitle":"Listen: Is perfect the enemy of the possible? Hear Thomas Curran in this episode of the LSE iQ podcast."}},{"type":"content","value":"\u003Ch2\u003EIs perfectionism a 21\u003Csup\u003Est\u003C\u002Fsup\u003E century problem?\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDr Curran emphasises the fact that many aspects of capitalism, such as competitive markets, materialism and consumer culture, have existed for most of the post-war era. But whether you are applying for a university, buying a car, or pursuing a career, 21\u003Csup\u003Est\u003C\u002Fsup\u003E century globalised cultures have widened the lens of comparison beyond our immediate peers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe constant presence of social media in people&rsquo;s lives since the late 2000s has also accelerated this trend he stresses: &ldquo;Images of others at carefully selected moments of their lives has distorted our perceptions of their lifestyles and careers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We are surrounded by these images and messages all the time, and have internalised unrealistic ideals and values. It is one of the reasons why we have seen a rapid rise of socially prescribed perfectionism and a lot of its allied mental health issues, such as negative body image, anorexia as well as malignant forms of mental health.&nbsp;Perfectionism is one piece of the puzzle when you think about some of the cultural changes we&rsquo;ve seen in the past two decades.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBy shifting the focus away from the individual to the social factors, Dr Curran aims to challenge the idea that these problems originate within ourselves, so that we can better understand the culture that gave rise to them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Perfection is impossible, but it can do real damage. I think that if we can challenge our own perfectionist tendencies, and be more honest and realistic with ourselves, our own better mental health and happiness will follow.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThomas Curran was speaking to Peter Carrol, Media Relations Officer at LSE.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EImage: Daniel Reche\u002FPexels.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"type":"callout","value":{"content":"\u003Cp\u003EThomas Curran&rsquo;s forthcoming book \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.thebookseller.com\u002Fnews\u002Fprofile-swiftly-pre-empts-perfectionism-book-one-largest-commitments-ever-made-publisher\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EImperfect\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E was published by Profile in 2021.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.apa.org\u002Fpubs\u002Fjournals\u002Freleases\u002Fbul-bul0000138.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPerfectionism Is Increasing Over Time\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E by Tom Curran and Andrew Hill was published in 2017 by the American Psychological Association.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"}},{"type":"subscribeCTA","value":{"button":{"link":{"entryTitle":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","entryDescription":null,"entryThumbnail":null,"sys":{"id":"c1172d9b-6099-482e-abe5-64edf41c84b8","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"link","dataFormat":"entry","uri":null}},"text":"Subscribe"},"link":{"entryTitle":"Research for the World newsletter sign up","entryDescription":null,"entryThumbnail":null,"sys":{"id":"c1172d9b-6099-482e-abe5-64edf41c84b8","language":"en-GB","contentTypeId":"link","dataFormat":"entry","uri":null}},"description":"\u003Cp\u003ESign up to receive our newsletter: a bi-monthly digest of the latest soci